l issue is **TLE**. For n=10, the search tree is enormous. Let me check: candidates per level \u2248 2 * |b| * n. At depth 9, with growing b, this could be 2*10*10 = 200 candidates at the deepest levels. 200^9 is way too large.\n\nHowever, given the constraints (t \u2264 20, n \u2264 10), and that early pruning via `covered()` check might help in practice... but worst case it's still exponential and likely TLEs.\n\nLet me verify with the test case `1 10 100` (n=3): Starting with {0}, depth=2. Candidates from {0}: \u00b11, \u00b110, \u00b1100. That's 6 candidates. For each, we get another ~8 candidates. Total: ~48 paths. This is fine for small n.\n\nFor n=10 though, this explodes. The worst case with n=10 would likely TLE.\n\n{\"verdict\": \"FAIL\", \"bugs\": [{\"description\": \"Exponential time complexity: for n=10, the search explores up to O((2*n*n)^n) paths without memoization or effective pruning, likely causing TLE\", \"line\": 28, \"severity\": \"critical\", \"triggering_input\": \"1\\n10\\n25 -171 250 174 152 242 100 -205 -258 1\"}, {\"description\": \"lru_cache is imported but never used - the recursive search has no memoization to avoid revisiting the same set of b values\", \"line\": 10, \"severity\": \"minor\", \"triggering_input\": \"\"}]}",
